{{Infobox cave | name = Gilindire Cave | other_name = Aynalıgöl Mağarası | photo = [[File:Aynalıgöl cave.JPG|250px]] | photo_width = | photo_caption = Stalactite in the cave | map = Turkey | relief = yes | map_width = | map_caption = Location of Gilindire Cave in Turkey | map_alt = | location = [[Aydıncık, Mersin]], [[Turkey]] | coordinates = {{coord|36|07|52|N|33|24|09|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coords_ref = | land_registry_number = | depth = | length = {{convert|555|m|ft|abbr=on}} | height_variation = {{convert|22|m|ft|abbr=on}} | elevation = | discovery = {{start date and age|1999}} | geology = | entrance_count = | entrance_list = | difficulty = | hazards = | access = | show_cave = | show_cave_length = | lighting = | visitors = | features = | survey = | survey_format = | website = }}
'''Gilindire Cave''' ({{lang-tr|Gilindire Mağarası}}), also known as '''Aynalıgöl Cave''', is a [[cave]] in [[Aydıncık, Mersin]], southern [[Turkey]]. It was discovered by a shepherd in 1999. Gilindire was the former name of the town Aydıncık until 1965.<ref name="r1"/>
==Location and access== Gilindire Cave is located approximately {{convert|7.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeast of Sancak Point and Kurtini Creek in the Aydıncık district, part of the [[Mersin Province]]. Its entrance faces the [[Mediterranean Sea]], and a small village lies in front of the cave. The cave is accessible by sea via a 1 1/2-hour boat trip from Aydıncık, or by land via a 15–minute walk from the [[Antalya]]-[[Mersin]] highway.<ref name="ktb"/><ref name="got"/> A steel stairway leads down to the cave's entrance from above.<ref name="r1"/><ref name="syh"/><ref name="h1"/>
==Description== Gilindire Cave stretches over an area of {{convert|107|ha|m2|abbr=on}}. Its entrance is on a cliff {{convert|46|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level. The cave has a total length of {{convert|555|m|ft|abbr=on}} and a clearance of {{convert|22|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name="syh"/><ref name="m1"/><ref name="z1"/> It is a horizontally-developed, polygenic-fossilized cave.<ref name="got"/>
The cave features a wealth of [[stalagmite]]s, [[stalactite]]s, as well as "pillar, wall and drapery dripstones, leakage stones and cave needles" which divide the interior into many chambers.<ref name="got"/> At the rear of the cave lies a {{convert|140|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|18|-|30|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide, and {{convert|5|-|47|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep lake surrounded by dripstones and pillars.<ref name="ktb"/><ref name="got"/> The cave is called Aynalıgöl (literally: Mirror Lake) in common parlance, in reference to the presence of the lake.<ref name="r1"/><ref name="syh"/><ref name="h1"/><ref name="hdn1"/><ref name="t"/>
Some parts of the cave's main gallery are inhabited by [[bat]]s. Outside the cave, the nearby bays are the habitat of the [[Mediterranean monk seal]].<ref name="ktb"/><ref name="got"/>
==Exploration== Gilindire Cave was discovered by a shepherd in 1999.<ref name="r1"/><ref name="hdn1"/> When the state-owned [[General Directorate of Mineral Research and Exploration (Turkey)|Mineral Research and Exploration Co.]] (MTA) undertook exploration works in the cave, they discovered the lake at the end of the cave, {{convert|450|m|ft|abbr=on}} from the entrance.<ref name="m1"/> In 2002, two Turkish photographers came to the cave by sea, and took photos for the magazine ''[[Atlas (magazine)|Atlas]]'' both in the cave and underwater in the lake. Archaeologists found potsherds in the cave belonging to the [[Neolithic|New Stone Age]], [[Chalcolithic|Copper Age]], and [[Bronze Age|Early Bronze Age]] periods.<ref name="r1"/>
According to a survey by experts, the cave was formed in the beginning of the transition phase after the last [[Glacial period|glacial climate change]] of the [[Quaternary Period]], when the Mediterranean Sea rose {{convert|70|m|ft|abbr=on}}, flooding the bottom of the cave.<ref name="t"/> The change in the hydrological regime helped preserve the cave formations such as stalagmites and stalactites.<ref name="t"/> Due to being under water, they have remained unaffected by atmospheric changes to the present day. The lake's water is [[brackish water|brackish]] to a depth of {{convert|12|m|ft|abbr=on}}, while deeper water is [[Saline water|saline]].<ref name="syh"/><ref name="h1"/><ref name="m1"/><ref name="z1"/>
In 2013, Gilindire Cave was designated a nature reserve by the [[Ministry of Forest and Water Management (Turkey)|Ministry of Forest and Water Management]].<ref name="m1"/><ref name="z1"/> It was opened to the public, and has become a tourist attraction.<ref name="got"/><ref name="syh"/><ref name="h1"/>
