{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} {{Use British English|date=February 2015}} '''Henry Nottidge Moseley''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (14 November 1844 – 10 November 1891) was a British [[natural history|naturalist]] who sailed on the global scientific expedition of [[Challenger expedition|HMS ''Challenger'']] in 1872 through 1876.
Moseley was born in Wandsworth, London, the son of [[Henry Moseley (mathematician)|Henry Moseley]]. He was educated at [[Harrow School]], at [[Exeter College, Oxford]] (Arts)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/alumnioxoniense01oxfogoog |title=Alumni oxonienses: the members of the University of Oxford, 1715-1886, vol.3|website=Archive.org|accessdate=2017-01-16}}</ref> and at the [[University of London]] (medicine). He married Amabel Gwyn Jeffreys, daughter of the conchologist [[John Gwyn Jeffreys]], in 1881, and they were the parents of the noted [[British people|British]] [[physics|physicist]] [[Henry Moseley|Henry Gwyn Jeffreys Moseley]].
Moseley delivered the [[Royal Society]] [[Croonian Lecture]] in 1878 and was elected as a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1879.He participated as [[naturalist]] in expeditions to [[Ceylon]], to [[California]], and to [[Oregon]], and most notably he was in the [[Challenger expedition|''Challenger'' expedition]] aboard {{HMS|Challenger}} of 1872 through 1876 which covered over {{convert|120,000|km|mi|abbr=on|0}} of the world's oceans. Moseley began working at the [[University of London]] in 1879, and he was awarded the [[Linacre Chair of Zoology|Linacre chair of human and comparative anatomy]] at [[Merton College, Oxford]] in 1881. In the same year, Moseley became involved in the negotiations for the donation of the Pitt-Rivers donation, which would form the [[Pitt Rivers Museum]] from 1884. Moseley, with [[Edward Burnett Tylor]], oversaw the transfer of Pitt-Rivers' collection from London to Oxford<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.prm.ox.ac.uk/rpr/index.php/article-index/12-articles/406-pitt-rivers-and-moseley |title=Pitt-Rivers and Moseley |website=Web.prm.ox.ac.uk |date=1920-09-24 |accessdate=2017-01-16}}</ref>
Moseley exerted significant influences on his noted students [[Halford Mackinder]]<ref>''Sir Halford Mackinder, 1861 - 1947: Some New Perspectives'', by Brian Blouet, Research Paper 13, School of Geography, University of Oxford 1975</ref> and [[Walter Garstang]], who changed his career choice from [[medicine]] to [[zoology]] under Moseley's supervision. Moseley was awarded the Royal Society's [[Royal Medal]] in 1887.
Moseley's publications include : * ''On Oregon''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001971350 |title=Catalog Record: Oregon: its resources, climate, people, and... &#124; Hathi Trust Digital Library |website=Catalog.hathitrust.org |date= |accessdate=2017-01-16}}</ref> (1878). * ''On the Structure of the Sylasteridae'' (1878). * ''Notes by a Naturalist on the Challenger''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001489855 |title=Catalog Record: Notes by a naturalist on the "Challenger",... &#124; Hathi Trust Digital Library |website=Catalog.hathitrust.org |date= |accessdate=2017-01-16}}</ref> (1879).
Moseley studied [[invertebrate]] biology and the [[phylogeny]] of [[arthropod]]s, [[coral]], and [[mollusc]]s.
Moseley is commemorated in the Latin name of the species, [[northern rockhopper penguin]], the ''Eudyptes moseleyi''.
